<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,510,895]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,547,571]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[830,917,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">phasma</emphasis>
(ghost), referring to the ghost-like appearance of the species; feminine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,510,895]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,618,643]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Berry, Beatty &amp; Proszy nski, 1998" authorityName="Berry, Beatty &amp; Proszy nski" authorityYear="1998" box="[454,963,614,643]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lakarobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[454,581,619,643]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Lakarobius</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Berry, J. W. &amp; Beatty, J. A. &amp; Proszy nski, J." box="[588,963,614,643]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="149 - 189" refId="ref30232" refString="Berry, J. W., Beatty, J. A. &amp; Proszy nski, J. (1998) Salticidae of the Pacific Islands. III. Distribution of seven genera with descriptions of nineteen new species and two new genera. Journal of Arachnology, 26, 149 - 189." type="journal article" year="1998">Berry, Beatty &amp; Prószyṅski, 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Thorell" authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1892" box="[1016,1183,618,643]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Bindax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1016,1095,619,643]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Bindax</emphasis>
Thorell
</taxonomicName>
(see Prószyṅski 1984) in body form and color pattern, but differs from them by the absence of a proximal tegular lobe and retrolateral sperm duct loop in the male palp (
<figureCitation box="[550,711,690,714]" captionStart="FIGURES 189–195" captionStartId="40.[151,263,1889,1912]" captionTargetBox="[157,1419,195,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-69@40.[151,1436,195,1868]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 189–195. Phasmolia elegans sp. nov. 189 male paratype, dorsal view; 190 female paratype, dorsal view; 191 male left palp, ventral view; 192 male left palp, retrolateral view; 193 female right chelicera, back view; 194 epigynum, ventral view; 195 cleared epigynum, dorsal view. Scale bars: 189–190, 0.5 mm; 191–195, 0.1 mm." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs 191–192</figureCitation>
). This genus can also be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berry, Beatty &amp; Proszy nski" authorityYear="1998" box="[1228,1355,691,715]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lakarobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1228,1355,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Lakarobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the chelicera with three promarginal teeth (
<figureCitation box="[605,705,726,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 189–195" captionStartId="40.[151,263,1889,1912]" captionTargetBox="[157,1419,195,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-69@40.[151,1436,195,1868]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 189–195. Phasmolia elegans sp. nov. 189 male paratype, dorsal view; 190 female paratype, dorsal view; 191 male left palp, ventral view; 192 male left palp, retrolateral view; 193 female right chelicera, back view; 194 epigynum, ventral view; 195 cleared epigynum, dorsal view. Scale bars: 189–190, 0.5 mm; 191–195, 0.1 mm." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 193</figureCitation>
; two in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berry, Beatty &amp; Proszy nski" authorityYear="1998" box="[803,929,726,750]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lakarobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,929,726,750]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Lakarobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and one bicuspid retromarginal tooth (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 189–195" captionStartId="40.[151,263,1889,1912]" captionTargetBox="[157,1419,195,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-69@40.[151,1436,195,1868]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 189–195. Phasmolia elegans sp. nov. 189 male paratype, dorsal view; 190 female paratype, dorsal view; 191 male left palp, ventral view; 192 male left palp, retrolateral view; 193 female right chelicera, back view; 194 epigynum, ventral view; 195 cleared epigynum, dorsal view. Scale bars: 189–190, 0.5 mm; 191–195, 0.1 mm." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 193</figureCitation>
; four cusps in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Berry, Beatty &amp; Proszy nski" authorityYear="1998" box="[372,498,763,787]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lakarobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[372,498,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Lakarobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the median septum of female epigynum, which is not continuous with the anterior rim of the window (
<figureCitation box="[489,592,798,822]" captionStart="FIGURES 189–195" captionStartId="40.[151,263,1889,1912]" captionTargetBox="[157,1419,195,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-69@40.[151,1436,195,1868]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 189–195. Phasmolia elegans sp. nov. 189 male paratype, dorsal view; 190 female paratype, dorsal view; 191 male left palp, ventral view; 192 male left palp, retrolateral view; 193 female right chelicera, back view; 194 epigynum, ventral view; 195 cleared epigynum, dorsal view. Scale bars: 189–190, 0.5 mm; 191–195, 0.1 mm." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 194</figureCitation>
). Also similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[802,900,798,822]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Athamas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[802,900,798,822]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Athamas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
O. P.—Cambridge (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Jendrzejewska, B." box="[1189,1423,798,822]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="181 - 190" refId="ref30552" refString="Jendrzejewska, B. (1995) Genus Athamas Pickard-Cambridge, 1877, an unusual salticid from the Pacific area (Araneae: Salticidae). Genus, 6, 181 - 190." type="journal article" year="1995">Jendrzejewska 1995</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Zabka, 1996" authorityName="Zabka" authorityYear="1996" box="[151,386,830,859]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Bulolia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,233,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Bulolia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zabka, M." box="[243,386,830,858]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="701 - 707" refId="ref31296" refString="Zabka, M. (1996) Bulolia, a new genus of Salticidae (Arachnida: Araneae) from Papua New Guinea. Revue suisse de Zoologie, vol. hors serie 2, 701 - 707." type="journal article" year="1996">Żabka, 1996</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Balogh, 1980 a" authorityName="Balogh" authorityYear="1980" box="[447,768,834,859]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Leptathamas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[447,592,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Leptathamas</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Balogh, P." box="[602,768,834,858]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="29 - 31" refId="ref30026" refString="Balogh, P. (1980 a) Studies on the Papuan Attidae (Araneae): Leptathamas paradoxus gen. et sp. n. Folia Entomologica Hungarica, 41, 29 - 31." type="journal article" year="1980">Balogh, 1980a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see Szű 
<bibRefCitation author="Szuts, T." box="[875,961,834,858]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="41 - 57" refId="ref31077" refString="Szuts, T. (2003) On remarkable jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae) from Papua New Guinea. Folia Entomologica Hungarica, 64, 41 - 57." type="journal article" year="2003">ts 2003</bibRefCitation>
) in the ALEs, which are posterior to the AMEs, but can be easily distinguished from them by the shape of the genitalic organs (
<figureCitation box="[1124,1395,870,894]" captionStart="FIGURES 189–195" captionStartId="40.[151,263,1889,1912]" captionTargetBox="[157,1419,195,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-69@40.[151,1436,195,1868]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 189–195. Phasmolia elegans sp. nov. 189 male paratype, dorsal view; 190 female paratype, dorsal view; 191 male left palp, ventral view; 192 male left palp, retrolateral view; 193 female right chelicera, back view; 194 epigynum, ventral view; 195 cleared epigynum, dorsal view. Scale bars: 189–190, 0.5 mm; 191–195, 0.1 mm." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs 191–192, 194–195</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
